This PR originally just dealt with the `DirectLimit` and `FinitelyGenerated` files - I included some more parts of the project after the fact.
I think those parts need a bit more work, so I've removed them from this PR, and will hopefully PR those soon.
Specifically, I think there should be a better definition of an "extension pair" or "back-and-forth pair" that indicates that any `PartialEquiv` of finitely generated substructures can be extended.

Sorry, this is going to be very vague as I am going off memory, but have you read this proof perl paper about back and forth arguments in Coq? Does your back and forth argument fit in their framework?

I hadn't read it - there are two notable differences. (If indeed this is what you mean: https://drops.dagstuhl.de/storage/00lipics/lipics-vol237-itp2022/LIPIcs.ITP.2022.22/LIPIcs.ITP.2022.22.pdf )

- One is that they're focusing on _computational_ aspects of it - I don't think it makes sense to try too hard to make things decidable right now, I'm aiming for some very classical logic settings.
- Also, they're implementing a finite partial isomorphism as literally a list in `X Ã— Y` with appropriate properties. These naturally induce isomorphisms between finite substructures, so I don't think this is an important difference. I have some more thoughts about this that I could convey better on Zulip.

Thanks!

or write out the appropriate lemmas yourself
I don't have a better name to suggest, but I should point out that this name reads like a Prop. Maybe you have an idea to improve it? Non-blocking, though

Would `cofinalMemDom` or `memDomCofinal` be better?
(It might read like a Prop one way or another, because cofinality is a subtype that easily could have been a Prop)

I would have guessed that it would be a predicate to be cofinal, but it seems to be implemented as a subtype of sets in analogy to ideals, where it does make sense to be bundled. I have no particularly strong opinion, as I'm not really aware of the other API features.
`Order.Ideal` is a half-baked file so I am willing to hear that the API is suboptimal. I will try writing you a `Final`/`Cofinal` API tomorrow.
To be clear - I don't have any real complaint, or even a clear request, with the `Order.Cofinal` API, in part because I didn't write any of the proofs that really use it here, @QuinnLesquimau did.
I guess this can be future work
